  <li id="comment-11543" class="comment even thread-even depth-1">
    <header class="comment--meta">
      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn"><a href="http://www.culinarysherpas.com" class="url" rel="ugc external nofollow">Culinary Sherpa #2</a></cite></div>
      <a href="https://orangette.net/2008/04/right-this-minute/#comment-11543"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2008-04-02T13:08:00-04:00">Wednesday, April 2, 2008 at 1:08 pm</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>Greetings from sunny Tampa, Molly. I&#8217;ve had to make pounds and pounds of aioli. I love the rustic nature of your arm-strong brew. </></>I; however, make it it the food processor. Omitting the vinegar.</></>Next time you make your aioli, try beating only the yolk until it becomes a thick, light yellow. Then add your flavoring (garlic and lemon), then (as you said)slowly add the olive oil. I have found, by taking the time to thicken the yolk first, it won&#8217;t break as easily when the citrus is added. Finally, add the Dijon at the very end. </>You, of course, have already become an accomplished Aioli maker, but you may find it to be a new twist. </><a href="http://www.culinarysherpas.com" rel="nofollow ugc">http://www.culinarysherpas.com</a></p>
    </div>

