  <li id="comment-11564" class="comment odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1">
    <header class="comment--meta">
      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn"><a href="https://www.blogger.com/profile/01493708300940204826" class="url" rel="ugc external nofollow">Molly</a></cite></div>
      <a href="https://orangette.net/2008/04/right-this-minute/#comment-11564"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2008-04-06T21:59:00-04:00">Sunday, April 6, 2008 at 9:59 pm</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>Rebecca, that&#8217;s a really good question about the yogurt.  To my palate, the yogurt in France tastes richer than what I can find here &#8211; even when it&#8217;s low-fat &#8211; and it isn&#8217;t terribly tart.  It&#8217;s <>wonderful<>.  I can&#8217;t say for certain, but I think the difference is mainly a function of the milk there, and of the bacteria involved.  Dairy products in France are wonderful in general.  (Although don&#8217;t get me wrong: you can still get mediocre yogurt there, too!)  As for brands of yogurt here in the US, I am a plain yogurt kind of person, and I often buy Brown Cow &#8211; low-fat or cream-top &#8211; which I like very much.  It&#8217;s not like French yogurt, but it&#8217;s good.  Also, when I&#8217;m on the East Coast, I always buy some < HREF="http://www.liberte.qc.ca/en/page.ch2?uid=Yogurt" REL="nofollow">Liberte<> yogurt, imported from Canada.  It reminds me very much of the French stuff.  So, SO good.</></>As for what the French eat for breakfast, it&#8217;s hard to say.  I don&#8217;t think there&#8217;s any one answer.  Everybody eats something different, just like us in the States. A very simple, everyday, traditional breakfast is what you&#8217;ve heard: a <>tartine<> (a buttered piece of toast or portion of baguette) with coffee of some sort.  But lots of French buy cereal these days, and of course there are all sorts of pastries and other things&#8230;</p>
    </div>

